div.p:
The Judgement of Hierom is so well known herein, that the Bishop of Spalato
De Repub. Ecclesiasticâ. Lib. 2. Cap. 4. Numb. 46. Sunt qui Hieronymum in rectam sententiam vel invitum velint trahere—neque in hoc aut excusari satis potest, aut &c. acknowledges that Hierom can by no means, yea not byforce be reconcil'd to their Cause. Hierome's Judgement (saith Saravia
De diversis gradibus ministrorum Evangelii. Cap. 23. Dico privatam fuisse Hieronymi opinionem, consentaneam cum Aërio &c.) was private; all one with that of Aërius, and contrary to the Word of GOD, wherefore we shall examine his Arguments. And on this account he is much offended with Hierome accusing him of Vanity, Ibid. 27. Self-contradiction Exam. tract. de triplici Episcopatû. Page 25., and Prevarication Ibid. Page 34.;

For First, Basil, in the forecited place, tells us, that Eustathius was
so cunning, as to perswade the ablest of these times that he was Orthodox;
and why might he not then put a Cheat on his own Presbytry.
